uffolk, England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moodye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Moody  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moody","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Middle English <i>mody</i> ‘proud, haughty, angry, fierce, bold, brave, or rash’ (Old English <i>mōdig</i>). Compare   Muddiman  . This English name has been established in Ireland since the late 13th century."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Moodye was born about 1380, in London, England, his father, Sir Hugh Moodye Jr, was 21 and his mother, Abigail Burbank, was 18. He married Lady Margaret Issobell. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1430, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1380–1430":"umbes 1380–1430","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1379":"1379","1467":"1467","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Harwich, Essex, England":"Harwich, Essex, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"about 1380–1430":"noin 1380–1430","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1363–Female":"1363–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","1379":"1379","1467":"1467","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Harwich, Essex, England":"Harwich, Essex, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"about 1380–1430":"environ 1380–1430","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1363–Female":"1363–Décédée","ab